)` for independent investigation.\n- You may use Lashlang background processes or subagents for work that should continue independently.\n- The red and blue UI buttons emit `ui.button.pressed`. Register `ui.button.pressed({})`; the selected button arrives in the event payload, not in the source config:\n\n```lash\nprocess on_button(event: ui.button.Pressed) {\n  wake { kind: \"button_pressed\", button: event.button, message: event.message }\n  finish true\n}\n\nhandle = await triggers.register({\n  source: ui.button.pressed({}),\n  target: on_button,\n  name: \"button watcher\"\n})?\nsubmit handle\n```\n\n- For schedule requests, build `cron.Schedule(...)` values and register a single-input process with `await triggers.register(...)`. Timers are host-owned; the workbench sidebar only advertises the schedule source instead of firing synthetic ticks.\n\nUse background processes or subagents only when they clarify the user's request or make parallel progress. Keep the visible answer concise and mention any background work you started.","type":"text"}],"role":"system"},{"content":[{"cache_control":{"type":"ephemeral"},"text":"--- history[0] · user message · 391 chars ---\n\nRegister a cron schedule trigger in Lashlang. Use process daily_digest(tick: cron.Tick) and access tick.fired_at. Build source = cron.Schedule({ expr: \"*/5 * * * *\", tz: \"UTC\" }). Register it with triggers.register({ source: source, target: daily_digest, name: \"cron smoke\" }) and submit the handle. Do not claim any tick has fired; this workbench only registers the host-owned timer source.","type":"text"}],"role":"user"},{"content":"\n\n\n=== CURRENT ITERATION: 1 ===\n\n\n=== FINALIZATION ===\n\nThe turn must finish through `submit <value>`. Prose alone does not end the turn.","role":"user"}],"model":"anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6","reasoning":{"effort":"high"},"stream":true,"stream_options":{"include_usage":true}},"endpoint":"chat/completions","type":"openai_compatible.request_body"}}}
